      "title": "The Scarcity Effect and Early-Bird Pricing",
      "content": "The scarcity effect is a powerful psychological principle stating that people place a higher value on items that are perceived as limited. In ticket sales, we leverage this through early-bird pricing. An early-bird discount is a price reduction offered for a limited time or a limited number of tickets, typically at the beginning of the sales cycle. Its primary purpose is twofold: to reward early commitment and to create urgency. By setting a clear deadline or a cap on the number of discounted tickets, you trigger a fear of missing out (FOMO) in potential attendees. This urgency compels customers to make a purchasing decision sooner rather than later, which is invaluable for event planning. It helps you secure baseline attendance and revenue early, de-risking the event. The key is to communicate the scarcity clearly: \"Only the first 100 tickets are at this price,\" or \"Early-bird pricing ends this Friday.\" This frames the discount not just as a saving, but as an opportunity that is fleeting and must be seized.",
      "title": "VIP Tiers and Value-Based Options"
