    {
      "content": "A price calendar is a strategic timeline that maps out your entire pricing structure from the moment tickets go on sale to the day of the event. It's your master plan for revenue optimization. This calendar typically starts with the lowest price point (the early-bird offer) and progressively increases the price as the event date approaches and ticket inventory decreases. A typical structure might be: Phase 1 (Super Early-Bird), Phase 2 (Early-Bird), Phase 3 (Standard Price), and Phase 4 (Last-Minute/At-the-Door Price). The key to a successful price calendar is clear communication. You must announce future price increases in advance. This reinforces the scarcity effect and rewards those who commit early. Adjusting prices according to a pre-defined calendar allows you to manage demand effectively. If sales are slow in a certain phase, you can hold the price or extend the deadline. If sales are exceptionally fast, you might move to the next price phase earlier than planned. The price calendar transforms pricing from a static decision into a dynamic tool for managing sales momentum.",
      "title": "Explaining Price Through Value, Not Cost"
